  <h2>Loot List Visibility</h2>
  <hr />
  <h6>
    Every submitted loot list, as well as the guild-wide loot list, will be publicly available to every raiding member of the guild. This is in the interest of full transparency as well as to ensure that the loot policy is fully auditable by any raiding member at any time.
    <br /><br />
    All raiding members of the guild, officer or otherwise, will abide by and be beholden to the guild-wide loot list. This removes any opportunity for human error during loot distribution.
  </h6>
  <hr class="divider">
  <h2>Loot List Oversight</h2>
  <hr />
  <h6>
    There will be no officer management or manipulation of loot lists except in exceptional circumstances (ex: A Holy Paladin stacking the top brackets of their loot list with non-bis cloth gear). This oversight will only come into play in situations where the submitted loot list is obviously and intentionally bogus.
    <br /><br />
    In such a situation, the submitted loot list will be rejected by an officer and the member that submitted this list will be asked to revise their list and re-submit it.
  </h6>
  <hr class="divider">
  <h2>Rerolling Policy</h2>
  <hr />
  <h6>
    As the above described loot lists are character-specific, any reroll would require that a new loot list is submitted.
    <br /><br />
    Due to the nature of having character-specific and guild-wide loot lists visible to every raiding member, any reroll will have their new loot list created with a bias (conscious or otherwise). Due to this, attendance bonuses for list values are also character-specific and thus a reroll would start with a fresh attendance score just as if they were a new Trial member. Additionally, there will be a 2-week probation period where this reroll is not able to accrue attendance points. After this 2-week period ends, the rerolled character would begin accruing attendance points which would build up and cap out after 10 weeks of attended raids.
  </h6>
